<HEAD>Thunderstorms Swirl Through South, Blast The West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms swirled through North Carolina, Virginia and Iowa
today, dumping much-needed rain on several areas, while another
storm system blasted Wyoming, Nevada and Utah with heavy winds and
large hail.
   In North Carolina, more than 2{ inches of rain fell between
Greensboro and Winston-Salem. At the airport near Greensboro, half
an inch of rain fell in 30 minutes. In Iowa, over an inch of rain
was recorded in Algona, Fort Dodge, and Kanawha.
   In Virginia, thunderstorms in Williamsburg brought 1\ inches of
rain Friday night and flooded some of the low-lying areas.
   Severe thunderstorms in Pulaski County in western Virginia
brought large hail that damaged cars, while wind gusts to over 50
mph knocked down trees.
   Thunderstorms also whipped up strong winds in western states.
Winds gusted to 59 mph in Great Falls, Mont.; to 53 mph at Trenton,
Utah; and to near 50 mph in Cody, Wyo. Further west, winds gusted
to nearly 60 mph at Carlin in northern Nevada.
   Skies were mostly clear this morning from the Great Lakes region
across the middle Mississippi Valley and central Plains to Texas,
as well as over northern Florida and much of California. Dense fog
hovered over portions of New England.
   Today's forecast called for widely scattered showers and
thunderstorms from the Carolinas across the Gulf Coast states,
Florida and the lower Mississippi Valley to southeast Texas, with
most of the storms centered in North Carolina; and widely scattered
thunderstorms in Minnesota and over the mountains of the West, with
most of the storms in northern Arizona, Utah and eastern Nevada.
   High temperatures were forecast for the 70s from New England
across New York into the northern Great Lakes; in the 60s and 70s
over the Pacific Northwest and along the California coast; between
95 and 100 across western portions of the Great Plains; near 105
degrees in the Big Bend area of southwest Texas; between 100 to 110
in the desert Southwest; and in the 80s to mid-90s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 44 at
Oscoda, Mich., to 94 at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 75 hazy; Boston 64 foggy; Buffalo 53 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 69 foggy; Cincinnati 60 fair; Cleveland 52 fair;
Detroit 61 fair; Miami 77 fair; New York 67 foggy; Philadelphia 69
foggy; Pittsburgh 51 fair; Portland, Maine 56 foggy; Washington 70
foggy.
   _Central: Bismarck 73 cloudy; Chicago 63 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
76 fair; Denver 69 fair; Des Moines 68 fair; Indianapolis 63 fair;
Kansas City 71 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 61 fair; Nashville 69
fair; New Orleans 74 foggy; St. Louis 73 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 74 fair; Anchorage 57 fair; Las Vegas 83
showery; Los Angeles 58 cloudy; Phoenix 93 partly cloudy; Salt Lake
City 66 fair; San Diego 62 cloudy; San Francisco 57 fair; Seattle
56 drizzle.
   _Canada: Montreal 55 fair; Toronto 48 fair.
